\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs32 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\f40\fs32\cf6\insrsid15095451\charrsid2622294 Second Half}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cf6\insrsid15095451\charrsid2622294 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s78\ql \fi720\li0\ri0\sa160\sl300\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2645883 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15095451\charrsid1593147 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 Having repeated my
 attempt three or four times, at last I felt exhausted and had no more strength to push and to be pushed, so I went aside and stood in a corner of the porch. And only then with great difficulty it began to dawn on me, and I began to understand the reason 
w
hy I was prevented from being admitted to see the life-giving Cross. The word of salvation gently touched the eyes of my heart and revealed to me that it was my unclean life which barred the entrance to me. I began to weep and lament and beat my breast, a
nd to sigh from the depths of my heart. And }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid5319348\charrsid2645883 so,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 
 I stood weeping when I saw above me the icon of the most holy Mother of God. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid2622294 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 And turning to her my bodily and spiritual eyes I said: `O Lady, Mother of God, who gave birth in the flesh to God the Word, I know
, O how well I know, that it is no honor or praise to thee when one so impure and depraved as I look up to thy icon, O ever-virgin, who didst keep thy body and soul in purity. Rightly do I inspire hatred and disgust before thy virginal purity. But I have 
h
eard that God Who was born of thee became man on purpose to call sinners to repentance. Then help me, for I have no other help. Order the entrance of the church to be opened to me. Allow me to see the venerable Tree on which He Who was born of thee suffer
e
d in the flesh and on which He shed His holy Blood for the redemption of sinners and for me, unworthy as I am. Be my faithful witness before thy son that I will never again defile my body by the impurity of fornication, but as soon as I have seen the Tree
 of the Cross I will renounce the world and its temptations and will go wherever thou wilt lead me.' 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid5319348\charrsid2645883 Thus,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 
 I spoke and as if acquiring some hope in firm faith and feeling some confidence in the mercy of the Mother of God, I left the place where I stood praying. And I went again and mingled with the crowd that was pushing its way into the temple. And no one
 seemed to thwart me, no one hindered my entering the church. I was possessed with trembling, and was almost in delirium. Having got as far as the doors which I could not reach before -- as if the same force which had hindered me cleared the way for me --
 
I now entered without difficulty and found myself within the holy place. And so it was I saw the life-giving Cross. I saw too the Mysteries of God and how the Lord accepts repentance. Throwing myself on the ground, I worshipped that holy earth and kissed 
it with trembling. The}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid1065548\charrsid2645883 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 
 I came out of the church and went to her who had promised to be my security, to the place where I had sealed my vow. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid2622294 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 And bending my knees before the Virgin Mother of God, I addressed to her such words as these: `O loving Lady, thou
 hast shown me thy great love for all men. Glory to God Who receives the repentance of sinners through thee. What more can I recollect or say, I who am so sinful? It is time for me, O Lady to fulfill my vow, according to thy witness. Now lead me by the ha
nd along the path of repentance!' }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid2622294 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 And at these words I heard a voice from on high: `If }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thou wilt}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  cross the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid5319348\charrsid2645883 Jordan,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thou wilt}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  find glorious rest.' 
\par Hearing this voice and having faith that it was for me, I cried to the Mother of God: `O Lady, Lady, do not forsake me!' 
\par With these words I left the porch of the church and set off on my journey. As I was leaving the church a stranger glanced at me and gave me three coins, saying: `Sister, take these.' 
\par And, taking the money, I bought three loaves and took them with me on my journey, as a blessed gift. I asked the person who sold the bread: `Which is the way to the 
Jordan?' I was directed to the city gate which led that way. Running on I passed the gates and still weeping 
went on my journey. Those I met I asked the way, and after walking for the rest of that day (I think it was nine o'clock when I saw the Cross) I at length reached at sunset the Church of St. John the Baptist which stood on the banks of the 
Jordan. After praying in the temple, I went down to the Jordan and rinsed my face and hands in its holy waters. I partook of the holy and life-giving Mysteries in the Church of the Forerunner and ate half of one of m
y loaves. Then, after drinking some water from Jordan, I lay down and passed the night on the ground. In the morning I found a small boat and crossed to the opposite bank. I again prayed to Our Lady to lead me whither she wished. Then I found
 myself in this desert and since then up to this very day I am estranged from all, keeping away from people and running away from everyone. And I live here clinging to my God Who saves all who turn to Him from faintheartedness and storms." 
\par 
\par Zosimas asked her: "How many years have gone by since }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thou}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  began to live in this desert?" 
\par She replied: "Forty-seven years have already gone by, I think, since I left the holy city." 
\par Zosimas asked: "But what food do}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 st}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 
thou}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  find?" 
\par 
\par The woman said: "I had two and a half loaves when I crossed the Jordan. Soon they dried up and became hard as rock. Eating a little I gradually finished them after a few years." 
\par Zosimas asked}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid2622294 : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 "Can it be that without getting ill }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 
thou hast}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  lived so many years thus, without suffering in any way from such a complete change?" 
\par The woman answered: "}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 Thou dost}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 
 remind me, Zosimas, of what I dare not speak of. For when I recall all the dangers which I overcame, and all the violent thoughts which confused me, I am again afraid that they will take possession of me." 
\par Zosimas said: "Do not hide from me anything; speak to me without concealing anything." 
\par And she said to him: "Believe me, Abba, seventeen years I passed in this desert fighting wild beasts -- mad desires and passions. When I was about to partake of food, I used to begin to regret the meat and fish of which I had so much in 
Egypt. I regretted also not having wine which I loved so much. For I drank a lot of wine when
 I lived in the world, while here I had not even water. I used to burn and succumb with thirst. The mad desire for profligate songs also entered me and confused me greatly, edging me on to sing satanic songs which I had learned once. But when such desires
 entered }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid5319348\charrsid2645883 me,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 
 I struck myself on the breast and reminded myself of the vow which I had made, when going into the desert. In my thoughts I returned to the icon of the Mother of God which had received me and to her I cried in prayer. I implored her to chase awa
y the thoughts to which my miserable soul was succumbing. And after weeping for long and beating my breast I used to see light at last which seemed to shine on me from everywhere. And after the violent storm, lasting calm descended. 
\par And how can I tell }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thee}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  about the thoughts which urged me on to fornication, how can I express them to }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thee}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 
, Abba? A fire was kindled in my miserable heart which seemed to burn me up completely and to awake in me a thirst for embraces. As soon as this craving came to me, I flu
ng myself on the earth and watered it with my tears, as if I saw before me my witness, who had appeared to me in my disobedience, and who seemed to threaten punishment for the crime. And I did not rise from the ground (sometimes I lay thus prostrate for a
 
day and a night) until a calm and sweet light descended and enlightened me and chased away the thoughts that possessed me. But always I turned to the eyes of my mind to my Protectress, asking her to extend help to one who was sinking fast in the waves of 
the desert. And I always had her as my Helper and the Accepter of my repentance. And }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid5319348\charrsid2645883 thus,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 
 I lived for seventeen years amid constant dangers. And since then even till now the Mother of God helps me in everything and leads me as it were by the hand." 
\par Zosimas asked: "Can it be that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thou}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  did}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 st}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  not need food and clothing?" 
\par 
\par She answered: "After finishing the loaves I had, of which I spoke, for seventeen years I have fed on herbs and all that can be found in the desert. The clothes I had when I crossed the 
Jordan became torn and worn out. I suffered greatly from the cold and greatly from the extreme heat. At times the sun burned me up and at other times I shivered from the frost, and frequently falling to the ground I lay wi
thout breath and without motion. I struggled with many afflictions and with terrible temptations. But from that time till now the power of God in numerous ways ha}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid3691649\charrsid2645883 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  guarded my sinful soul and my humble body. When I only reflect on the evils from which Our Lord has delivered }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid5319348\charrsid2645883 me,}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  I have imperishable food for hope o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid3691649\charrsid2645883 f}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 
 salvation. I am fed and clothed by the all-powerful Word of God, the Lord of all. For it is not by bread alone that man lives. And those who have stripped off the rags of sin have no refuge, hiding themselves in the clefts of the rocks 
(Job 24; Heb. 11:38)." 
\par Hearing that she cited words }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid3691649\charrsid2645883 of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 Scripture, from Moses and Job, Zosimas asked her: "And so }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thou hast}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  read the psalms and other books?" 
\par She smiled at this and said to the elder: "Believe }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid6315010 m}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 e, I have not seen a human face ever since I crossed the Jordan, except }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thy }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 
s today. I have not seen a beast or a living being ever since I came into the desert. I never learned from books. I have never even heard anyone who sang an
d read from them. But the word of God which is alive and active, by itself teaches a man knowledge. And }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid5319348\charrsid2645883 so,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 
 this is the end of my tale. But, as I asked }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thee}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  in the beginning, so even now I implore }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thee}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  for the sake of the Incarnate word of God, to pray to the Lord for me who am such a sinner." 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid5319348\charrsid2645883 Thus,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  concluding her }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid6315010\charrsid2645883 tale,}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  she bowed down before him. And with tears the elder exclaimed: 
"Blessed is God Who creates the great and wondrous, the glorious and marvelous without end. Blessed is God Who has shown me how He rewards those who fear Him. Truly, O Lord, Thou dost not forsake those who seek Thee!" 
\par And the woman, not allowing the elder to bow down before her, said: "I beg }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thee}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 
, holy father, for the sake of Jesus Christ our God and Savior, tell no one what }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thou hast}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 
 heard, until God delivers me of this earth. And now depart in peace and again next year }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thou}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  shal}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  see me, and I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thee}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 , if God will preserve us in His great mercy. But for God's sake, do as I ask }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thee}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 . Next year during Lent do not cross the Jordan, as is }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thy }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 
custom in the monastery." 
\par Zosimas was amazed to hear that she }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid5319348 knew }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 the rules of the monastery and could only say: 
"Glory to God Who bestows great gifts on those who love Him." 
\par She continued: "Remain, Abba, in the monastery. And even if }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thou}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 dost }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 wish to depart, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thou}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  wil}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 
 not be to do so. And at sunset of the holy day of the Last Supper, put some of the life-giving Body and Blood of Christ into a holy vessel worthy to hold such Mysteries for me, and bring it. And wait for me on the banks of the Jordan adjoini
ng the inhabited parts of the land, so that I can come and partake of the life-giving Gifts. For, since the time I communicated in the temple of the Forerunner before crossing the Jordan even to this day I have not approached the Holy Mysteri
es. And I thirst for them with irrepressible love and longing. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid5319348 A}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 nd }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs44\insrsid5319348\charrsid2645883 therefore,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  I ask and implore }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thee}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  to grant me my wish, bring me the life-giving Mysteries at the very hour when Our Lord made His disciples partake of His Divine Supper. Tell John the Abbot of the monastery where }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thou dost}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  live: Look to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thy }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 self and to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid6315010\charrsid2645883 thy brothers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 
, for there is much that needs correction. Only do not say this now, but when God guides }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thee}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 . Pray for me!" 

\par With these words she vanished in the depths of the desert. And Zosimas, falling down on his knees and bowing down to the ground on which she had stood, sent up glory and thanks to God. And, after wandering th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs44\insrsid6315010 rough}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  the desert, he returned to the monastery on the day all the brothers returned. 
\par For the whole year he kept silent, not daring to tell anyone of what he had seen. But in his }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid5319348\charrsid2645883 soul,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 
 he prayed to God to give him another chance of seeing the ascetic's dear face. And when at length the first Sunday of the Great Fast came, all went out into th
e desert with the customary prayers and the singing of psalms. Only Zosimas was held back by illness -- he lay in a fever. And then he remembered what the saint had said to him: "and even if }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thou}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 dost }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 wish to depart, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thou wilt}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  not be able to do so." 
\par Many
 days passed and at last recovering from his illness he remained in the monastery. And when again the monks returned and the day of the Last Supper dawned, he did as he had been ordered. And placing some of the most pure Body and Blood into a small chalic
e and putting some grapes and dates and lentils soaked in water into a small basket, he departed for the desert and reached the banks of the Jordan and sat down to wait for the saint. He waited for a long while and then began to doubt. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid2622294 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 Then raising his eyes to heaven, he began to pray: 
"Grant me O Lord, to behold that which Thou hast allowed be to behold once. Do not let me depart in vain, bearing the burden of my sins." 
\par And then another thought struck him: "And what if she does come? There is no boat; how will she cross the Jordan to come to me who am so unworthy?" 
\par And as he was pondering }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid5319348\charrsid2645883 thus,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 
 he saw the holy woman appear and stand on the other side of the river. Zosimas got up rejoicing and glorifying and thanking God. And }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid5319348\charrsid2645883 again,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  the thought came to him that she could not cross the Jordan. Then he saw that she made the sign of the Cross over the waters of the 
Jordan (and the night was a moonlight one, as he related afterwards) and then she at once stepped on to the waters and began walking across the surface towards him. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid2622294 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 And when he wanted to prostrate himself, she cried to him while still walking on the water: "What ar}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 t}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thou}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  doing, Abba, }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thou}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  ar}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  a priest and carrying the divine Gifts!" 
\par He obeyed her and on reaching the shore she said to the elder: "Bless, father, bless me!" 
\par 
\par He answered her trembling, for a state of confusion had overcome him at the sight of the miracle: "Truly God did not lie when He promised that when we purify ourselves we shall be 
like Him. Glory to Thee, Christ our God, Who has shown me through this thy slave how far away I stand from perfection." 
\par Here the woman asked him to say the Creed and our Father. He began, she finished the prayer and according to the custom of that time gave him the kiss of peace on the lips. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid2622294 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 Having partaken of the Holy Mysteries, she raised her hands to heaven and sighed with tears in her eyes, exclaiming: 
"Now lettest Thou Thy servant depart in peace, O Lord, according to Thy word; for my eyes have seen Thy salvation." 
\par Then she said to the elder: "Forgive me, Abba, for asking }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thee}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 
, but fulfill another wish of mine. Go now to the monastery and let God's grace guard }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thee}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 . }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid3691649\charrsid2645883 A}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 nd next year come again to the same place where I first met }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thee}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 . Come for God's sake, for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thou}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  shal}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  again see me, for such is the will of God." 
\par He said to her: "From this day on I would like to follow }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thee}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  and always see }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 
\ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid5319348\charrsid2645883 thy holy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  face. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid3691649\charrsid2645883 B}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 ut now fulfill the one and only wish of an old man and take a little of the food I have brought for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thee}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 ." 
\par And he showed her the basket, while she just touched the lentils with the tips of her fingers, and taking three grains said that the Holy Spirit guards the substance of the soul unpolluted. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid2645883 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 Then she said: "Pray, for God's sake pray for me and remember a miserable wretch." 
\par Touching the saint's feet and asking for her prayers for the Church, the kingdom and himself, he let her depart with tears, wh
ile he went off sighing and sorrowful, for he could not hope to vanquish the invincible. Meanwhile she again made the sign of the Cross over the Jordan, and stepped on to the waters and crossed over as before. And the elder returned filled wi
th joy and terror, accusing himself of not having asked the saint her name. But he decided to do so next year. 
\par And when another year had passed, he again went into the desert. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid13046565\charrsid2645883 He }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 
reached the same spot but could see no sign of anyone. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid5319348 S}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid5319348\charrsid2645883 o,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  raising his eyes to heaven as before, he prayed: "Show me, O Lord, Thy pure treasure, which Thou hast concealed in the desert. Show me, I pray Thee, the angel in the flesh, of which the world is not worthy." 
\par Then on the opposite bank of the river, her face turned towar
ds the rising sun, he saw the saint lying dead. Her hands were crossed according to custom and her face was turned to the East. Running up he shed tears over the saint's feet and kissed them, not daring to touch anything else. 
\par For a long }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid5319348\charrsid2645883 time,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  he wept. Th
en reciting the appointed psalms, he said the burial prayers and thought to himself: "Must I bury the body of a saint? Or will this be contrary to her wishes?" }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid2645883 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 And then he saw words traced on the ground by her head: "Abba Zosimas, bury on this spot the b
ody of humble Mary. Return to dust that which is dust and pray to the Lord for me, who departed in the month of Fermoutin of Egypt, called April by the Romans, on the first day, on the very night of our Lord's Passion, after having partaken of the Divine 
Mysteries." }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\fs20\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 [St. Mary died in 522 A. D.]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  
\par Reading this the elder was glad to know the saint's name. He understood too that as soon as she had partaken of the Divine Mysteries on the shore of the Jordan she was at once transported to the place
 where she died. The distance which Zosimas had taken twenty days to cover, Mary had evidently traversed in an hour and had at once surrendered her soul to God. 
\par Then Zosimas thought: "It is time to do as she wished. But how am I to dig a grave with nothing in my hands?" 
\par And then he saw nearby a small piece of wood left by some traveler in the desert. Picking it up he began to dig the ground. But the earth was hard and dry and did not yield to the efforts of the elder. He grew tired and covered with swea
t. He sighed from the depths of his soul and lifting up his eyes he saw a big lion standing close to the saint's body and licking her feet. At the sight of the lion he trembled with fear, especially when he called to mind Mary's words that she had never s
e
en wild beasts in the desert. But guarding himself with the sign of the cross, the thought came to him that the power of the one lying there would protect him and keep him unharmed. Meanwhile the lion drew nearer to him, expressing affection by every move
ment. 
\par Zosimas said to the lion: "The Great One ordered that her body was to be buried. But I am old and have not the strength to dig the grave (for I have no spade and it would take too long to go and get one), so can}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 st}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid10502878\charrsid2645883 thou}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883  carry out the work with }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid5319348\charrsid2645883 thy claws}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 
? Then we can commit to the earth the mortal temple of the saint." 
\par While he was still speaking the lion with his front paws began to dig a hole deep enough to bury the body. 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid5319348\charrsid2645883 Again,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 
 the elder washed the feet of the saint with his tears and calling on her to pray for all, covered the body with earth in the presence of the lion. I
t was as it had been, naked and uncovered by anything but the tattered cloak which had been given to her by Zosimas and with which Mary, turning away, had managed to cover part of her body. Then both departed. The lion went off into the depth of the deser
t
 like a lamb, while Zosimas returned to the monastery glorifying and blessing Christ our Lord. And on reaching the monastery he told all the brothers about everything, and all marveled on hearing of God's miracles. And with fear and love they kept the mem
ory of the saint. 
\par Abbot John, as St. Mary had previously told Abba Zosimas, found a number of things wrong in the monastery and got rid of them with God's help. And Saint Zosimas died in the same monastery, almost attaining the age of a hundred, and passe
d to eternal life. The monks kept this story without writing it down and passed it on by word of mouth to one another. 
\par But I (adds Sophronius) as soon as I heard it, wrote it down. Perhaps someone else, better informed, has already written the life of the Saint, but as far as I could, I have recorded everything, putting truth above all else. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 
\ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid3691649\charrsid2645883 M}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs44\insrsid15095451\charrsid2645883 
ay God Who works amazing miracles and generously bestows gifts on those who turn to Him with faith, reward those who seek light for themselves in this story, who hea
r, read and are zealous to write it, and may He grant them the lot of blessed Mary together with all who at different times have pleased God by their pious thoughts and labors. 
\par And let us also give glory to God, the eternal King, that He may grant us too 
His mercy in the day of judgment for the sake of Jesus Christ our Lord, to Whom belongs all glory, honor, dominion and adoration with the Eternal Father and the Most Holy and Life-giving Spirit, now and always, and though all ages. Amen. 
